## Why It Happens

Brake pads are the most frequently replaced component because they're designed to wear — that's their job. Most pads last between 30,000 and 70,000 miles depending on driving habits, vehicle weight, and the type of pad installed. What accelerates wear is driving style: frequent hard stops, heavy loads, and stop-and-go city driving all shorten pad life considerably. Montana's terrain — lots of elevation change and highway driving — affects wear patterns differently than purely urban use.

Rotors last longer than pads but fail in specific ways. The most common is warping from heat cycling: repeated hard stops heat the rotor unevenly, causing slight thickness variations that produce the pulsation drivers feel through the pedal. Rust pitting is also common in climates with road salt or moisture exposure, and once the surface is compromised, pad wear accelerates. Rotors have a minimum thickness specification — once they reach it, they can't safely absorb and dissipate heat.

Calipers and their slide pins are a less obvious but significant failure point. The slide pins allow the caliper to float and apply even pressure across the rotor. When the high-temperature grease on those pins dries out or gets contaminated, the pins stick. A sticking caliper keeps the pad in constant light contact with the rotor, which causes accelerated wear on one side, excess heat, and eventually a dragging sensation while driving. Hydraulic issues — air in the lines, a failing master cylinder, or a swollen brake hose — show up as a soft pedal or delayed engagement.

