## How We Diagnose It

### Inspect
We start with a visual inspection of all four corners: pad thickness, rotor condition (scoring, rust, minimum thickness), caliper movement, brake hose condition, and fluid level and color in the master cylinder reservoir. Brake fluid that's dark or has visible debris indicates moisture contamination, which lowers the fluid's boiling point and points to a flush being needed regardless of other findings.

### Test
We measure rotor thickness with a micrometer and check runout with a dial indicator — runout above manufacturer spec is a reliable indicator of warping even before a driver notices pedal pulsation. We check caliper slide pins for binding by hand and assess whether pistons are retracting properly after brake application. If an ABS or brake warning light is present, we pull fault codes with a scan tool to identify which wheel speed sensor or module is involved.

### Confirm
Before recommending any repair, we compare measurements against OEM specifications and confirm the root cause. A soft pedal doesn't automatically mean a master cylinder replacement — we'll pressure-test the system and check for leaks at each line and hose connection first. A pull to one side gets traced to a specific corner before parts are quoted.

### Repair
After completing repairs, we verify stopping performance with a road test and confirm pedal feel is firm and consistent. If calipers were serviced or replaced, we confirm even pad contact across the rotor face. Any ABS faults are cleared and we verify the light doesn't return before the vehicle leaves.

